<div class="ru-top-story">
<h6 class="kicker"></h6>
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">BNP Paribas, under investigation for doing business with Sudan and other countries that the United States has blacklisted, is weeks away from having its parent company plead guilty to the crime. But several months ago, BNP thought it had a secret weapon to avoid that fate altogether, <b><a href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/06/03/bnp-paribas-pinned-hopes-on-legal-memo-in-vain">DealBookâs Jessica Silver-Greenberg and Ben Protess write</a></b>. BNP showed prosecutors a memo that the bank thought would explain and possibly mitigate its conduct.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The memo essentially <b>authorized the bank to process certain transactions</b> for Sudan as long as BNPâs employees in New York were not involved with the arrangement. BNP said it followed the law firmâs directive, using a legal argument known as the âadvice of counselâ defense. But the prosecutors concluded that the memo, drafted in 2004 by a well-respected outside law firm, did not cover most of the conduct in question. Even so, the deliberations encapsulate the bankâs broader struggles to soften the blow of the criminal case and underscore the great lengths to which the bank has gone in trying to contain the fallout.</p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story --></p>
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title">PUNISHMENTS TO FIT THE CRIME <span class="divider">Â |Â </span></span><!-- end .title --> As they seek a suitable punishment for BNP Paribas, American regulators are turning their attention to the depths of the banking system, <b><a href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/06/03/regulators-explore-options-for-suitable-penalties-in-bnps-sanctions-inquiry">Peter Eavis writes in DealBook</a></b>. The bank is already facing a number of potential punishments, including a fine of about $8 billion, but some regulators are also considering restrictions on the BNP Paribas operations that funnel billions of dollars through the network that connects the worldâs largest banks.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Benjamin M. Lawsky, New York Stateâs top financial regulator, is said to be considering whether to <b>temporarily suspend BNP Paribasâs ability to process transactions</b> through its New York operations on behalf of foreign clients, an activity known as dollar clearing. Dollar clearing may not in itself generate large profits, but it plays a crucial role in moving money between the bank and its clients in its core businesses, like lending and trading.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><b>Mr. Eavis writes</b>: âThe fact that regulators are considering restrictions on such an important banking activity has added a significant twist to the debate over how to punish large banks.â The question now is whether regulators can isolate a certain type of clearing and if so, what the potential consequences of this punishment would be.</p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story --></p>
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title">IN DEFENSE OF THE PROFIT MOTIVE <span class="divider">Â |Â </span></span><!-- end .title --> The proposed acquisition of the Charleston Law School by the InfiLaw System â which runs three for-profit law schools and is owned by the private equity firm Sterling Partners â has set up a collision between the notion of legal education and the profit motive, <b><a href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/06/03/sale-of-law-school-raises-debate-over-who-should-profit">Steven M. Davidoff writes in the Deal Professor column</a></b>. But why is a for-profit private equity firm any worse than the current owners, who have made tens of millions of dollars off the schoolâs students in the last few years?</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#8220;<b>It all may just boil down to snobbery</b> and who should be allowed to attend law school,â Mr. Davidoff writes. With everyone looking to profit, the real fear may be that a private equity firm will lower standards. Rather than argue about who will profit from them, Mr. Davidoff adds, âCharlestonâs students may instead want to ask who will give South Carolinaâs residents the best opportunity to succeed as lawyers at an acceptable price.â</p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story --></p>
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title">ON THE AGENDA <span class="divider">Â |Â </span></span><!-- end .title --> <b>Big day for economic data</b>: The <b>ADP private payroll report</b> for May is out at 8:15 a.m. Data on <b>international trade</b> is released at 8:30 a.m. The second reading of first-quarter <b>productivity and costs</b> is out at 8:30 a.m. The <b>purchasing managersâ index for services</b> is out at 9:45 a.m. The <b>ISM nonmanufacturing index</b> for May is out 10 a.m. The Fedâs regular report on economic activity across the country, a report known as the <b>beige book</b>, is out at 2 p.m.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><b>TV watch</b>: The New York Rangers and the Los Angeles Kings take the ice for the <b>first game of the Stanley Cup finals</b> at 8 p.m. Eastern Time.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><b>On the Hill</b>: The Senate <b>Subcommittee on Financial Institutions and Consumer Protection</b> holds a hearing at 10 a.m. to examine student loan servicing. The <b>Senate Budget Committee</b> also holds a hearing at 10 a.m. on the impact of student loan debt on borrowers and the economy.</p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story --></p>
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title">PUTTING THE BANK BACK IN BANKER <span class="divider">Â |Â </span></span><!-- end .title --> Since the financial crisis, Goldman Sachs, like the rest of Wall Street, has had to find ways to diversify how it makes money as traditionally lucrative businesses have dried up. Now, as Goldman Sachsâs new chief strategy officer, Stephen M. Scherr must help the bank continue to expand operations like wealth management and lending, <b><a href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/06/03/for-goldmans-new-strategy-officer-putting-the-bank-back-in-banker">DealBookâs Rachel Abrams writes</a></b>. In his new role, Mr. Scherr will look for ways for the bank to grow across the whole firm.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Goldmanâs emphasis on traditional lending and asset management follows the lead of Morgan Stanley, its closest competitor. But Goldman <b>still relies heavily on its trading operations</b> to generate big profits, even as its return on equity, a measure of profitability, is far below what it was before the crisis. To reap higher returns, the bank has begun acquiring smaller asset managers. It also hopes to make more loans, including to high net worth clients.</p>
</div>
